Your job is to accomplish the task above and end your turn with
exactly ONE fenced `handoff` block reporting the result. Use any
tools your role grants — your role's manifest entry (or your
`## Loaded skills` block) declares what is available. Treat tool
calls as the LAST resort after you have used the resolved
context above. If the task needs a query and the relevant
schema is already in `[Resolved depends_on]`, compose the query
straight from those fields and run it; only call discovery / schema
tools when the resolved context is genuinely insufficient.

If a tool returns the same error twice in a row on an identical
payload, the third retry will not help — switch tactics (call a
different tool, rephrase the query, narrow the scope) or emit
`status: "error"` with the diagnostic so the planner can amend.

Tool-less roles (workers whose role grants no domain tools) skip
straight to the fence and describe the outcome in plain text — the
task brief tells you which mode you are in.

Reply with EXACTLY ONE fenced block as your TERMINAL message:

```handoff
{"status":"ok","body":"<short result text OR structured object — what the task accomplished>","memory_summary":"<one-line summary of what you learned>"}
```

The triple-backticks and the word `handoff` are mandatory; the
JSON inside must parse. If the task cannot be completed, emit
`status: "error"` and a `reason` field — the mission's planner
will read it and replan instead of aborting:

```handoff
{"status":"error","reason":"<one-sentence cause — name the missing tool / data / clarification>","memory_summary":"<one line>"}
```

Optional `satisfies` field — when your output produces evidence
that meets one or more `ac-N` rows from `[Mission acceptance
criteria]` (visible in your first message when the spawning skill
carries one), list those ids:

```handoff
{"status":"ok","body":{...},"memory_summary":"...","satisfies":["ac-1","ac-3"]}
```

The runtime marks those rows satisfied with evidence stamped from
your handoff. Only list ids whose CURRENT TURN materially produced
the evidence — re-confirming rows the prior wave already
satisfied is harmless but noisy. Unknown ids are silently skipped;
already-satisfied rows are not overwritten (checker / planner
authority wins). Status updates only — you cannot add, rewrite,
or drop AC; the planner owns the contract.

Notes:
- Intermediate tool calls and assistant prose during the turn are
  fine. The runtime parses ONLY the terminal fenced block.
- Do NOT narrate after the fence — anything past it is ignored.
- The `body` may be a plain string or a structured JSON object;
  pick whichever shape best carries the result. `body` MUST be
  present on `status: "ok"`.
- **Large or per-row results go to a FILE, not into the handoff.**
  The handoff is a JSON string bounded by your output budget — a
  long row list (one row per item, many rows) or a multi-MB payload
  overflows it, truncates mid-JSON, and the whole handoff fails to
  parse even when the work was correct. When the result is big,
  write it to a file in your working directory and put the file
  `path` plus a short summary (counts / totals / shape) in the
  `body`. Your working directory is SHARED by every worker in this
  mission, so a later worker reads your file straight from that
  path. Keep inline `body` for scalars and small summaries.
